{"author":{"id":"4bb6c1767e50694cfde61856db22bf137d1651e8a0b5ca858c486db3dd02f280"},"ops":[{"type":1,"timestamp":1778550202,"nonce":"xQYvavVt4RsyybZmvci1wVoUtk0=","title":"Preserve gitignored artifacts when worktree is removed post-merge","message":"## Problem\n\nWhen a feature worktree generates gitignored artifacts (e.g. HTML figure renders in `_artifacts/`) during work, those artifacts live inside the worktree's directory tree at `worktrees/\u003cbranch\u003e/_artifacts/`. When `mandible auth merge` completes and calls `dwt` to clean up the worktree, the gitignored content is silently deleted with it.\n\n### Concrete incident (issue `f47abb1`)\n\n- Subagent generated 6 figure HTMLs at `worktrees/feature__lit-replication-results/_artifacts/f47abb1/figures/*/figure.html`\n- The branch's `results/.../spec.json` files were committed and reached `main`\n- After auth merge, the worktree was deleted, taking the HTML files with it\n- Main repo's `_artifacts/f47abb1/figures/` was empty — symlinks in `results/` dangled\n- Workaround: re-run the analysis script from main to regenerate the HTMLs\n\n### Root cause mechanism\n\n`rlrmp/src/rlrmp/paths.py` derives `REPO_ROOT` from `Path(__file__).resolve().parent.parent.parent`. When a script runs from a worktree, `__file__` resolves to `worktrees/\u003cbranch\u003e/src/rlrmp/paths.py`, so `REPO_ROOT` points at the worktree directory and `_artifacts/` writes go there, not to the main repo's `_artifacts/`. The same mechanism applies in `feedbax/plot/io.py`'s `_find_repo_root`: it walks up from the package's `__file__` until it finds `.git`, which resolves to the worktree (worktrees share the same `.git` via git worktree). Worktree `.git` files are refs/pointers, not full repos, but they are regular files named `.git`, not directories — so the current walk may or may not find the correct root depending on implementation. Either way, the result is the same: artifacts land in the worktree directory.\n\n## Design space\n\n### (a) DWT-level: copy gitignored patterns before removing\n\nBefore `git worktree remove`, `dwt` reads a per-project pattern list (e.g. from `.worktree.yaml`) and rsyncs matching gitignored content from the worktree to the main repo root.\n- **Pros**: automatic, no agent diligence required; one place to implement; `.worktree.yaml` infrastructure already exists in rlrmp and dotfiles (`wt`, `wt-sync` already process it).\n- **Cons**: runs on every dwt invocation; requires pattern config per project; copy happens at delete time — if the worktree is force-removed or deleted outside dwt, content is still lost.\n- **Scope**: dotfiles repo (`dwt` binary + `.worktree.yaml` schema extension).\n\n### (b) Mandible-level: preserve hook before worktree cleanup\n\nIn `cleanup_merged_worktrees` (auth-merge.sh:325), before calling `dwt`, run a project-aware hook that syncs configured patterns to main.\n- **Pros**: fires at the right moment (post-auth-merge, pre-delete); already has repo context; can be project-aware via `.worktree.yaml`.\n- **Cons**: touches mandible repo AND requires dotfiles/rlrmp `.worktree.yaml` update anyway; mandible's `cleanup_merged_worktrees` calls a vendored `dwt` — adding artifact sync there means duplicating this logic in two places (dwt and mandible's copy).\n- **Scope**: mandible repo + dotfiles/rlrmp.\n\n### (c) Convention-only: rsync before auth request\n\nAgents are instructed (CLAUDE.md) to always copy `_artifacts/` from worktree to main BEFORE running `mandible auth request`.\n- **Pros**: zero implementation cost.\n- **Cons**: depends entirely on agent diligence; easily forgotten; doesn't help when mandible merges automatically or when agents skip the step.\n- **Scope**: CLAUDE.md only.\n\n### (d) Symlink _artifacts/ across worktrees (option e from task spec)\n\nAdd `_artifacts` to `.worktree.yaml`'s `shared` list. `wt` already symlinks entries in `shared` from the repo root into every new worktree. All artifact writes go to the main repo's `_artifacts/` regardless of which worktree the script runs from — the worktree's `_artifacts/` IS the main repo's `_artifacts/`.\n- **Pros**: solves the problem structurally — no copy needed because artifacts never live in the worktree in the first place; zero change to scripts; no timing dependency; consistent with existing pattern (`data/`, `private/` are already shared this way in dotfiles).\n- **Cons**: all worktrees share one `_artifacts/` — concurrent parallel worktrees could produce colliding writes if they work on the same experiment/run IDs (unusual but possible). On new worktree creation from a fresh checkout, `_artifacts/` must already exist in the main repo for the symlink to be created (`wt-sync` warns and skips if source is missing; scripts that mkdir will create it in the worktree, bypassing the symlink).\n- **Scope**: rlrmp only (add to `.worktree.yaml`). No dotfiles changes needed — `wt`/`wt-sync` already handle the symlink mechanism.\n\n### (e) Rewrite REPO_ROOT to always resolve to main worktree\n\nChange `paths.py` (and optionally feedbax `_find_repo_root`) to detect worktree context and return the main worktree root instead of the worktree directory. Can be done by checking for a `.git` FILE (worktree) vs a `.git` DIRECTORY (main worktree).\n- **Pros**: fixes the root cause; scripts become worktree-aware.\n- **Cons**: more invasive; may have unintended side effects if a worktree SHOULD have its own `_artifacts/` (e.g. experimental data that should not pollute main); requires feedbax change too.\n- **Scope**: rlrmp + feedbax.\n\n## Recommendation: Option (d) — symlink _artifacts/ via .worktree.yaml\n\nAdd a `.worktree.yaml` to rlrmp with `_artifacts` in the `shared` list. This:\n\n1. Uses existing, tested infrastructure (`wt` and `wt-sync` already process `.worktree.yaml`).\n2. Requires a single-file, 4-line change in rlrmp.\n3. Solves the problem structurally — no copy needed at delete time.\n4. Generalizes cleanly: any project can opt in to this behavior by adding to `.worktree.yaml`.\n5. Is consistent with the existing `shared:` pattern used in dotfiles for `private/`.\n\n**Implementation**: create `rlrmp/.worktree.yaml`:\n\n```yaml\nshared:\n  - _artifacts\n```\n\nAnd create `_artifacts/` in the main repo root if it doesn't exist (it does: `ls _artifacts/` shows content).\n\n**Caveat to document**: `_artifacts/` must exist in main repo root before running `wt`. If a developer clones fresh and the directory doesn't exist, the symlink won't be created. Mitigation: add a `setup` command to `.worktree.yaml` that creates the directory (`mkdir -p _artifacts`).\n\n**Parallel worktree collision**: if two worktrees run analyses for the same experiment+figure at the same time, writes could collide. This is rare in practice (analysis scripts are run sequentially, not concurrently) and acceptable given the simplicity of the fix.\n\n## Implementation details\n\n- **File to create**: `rlrmp/.worktree.yaml`\n- **Mechanism**: `wt` reads `.worktree.yaml`'s `shared:` list and calls `ln -sfn $repo_root/$item $wt_dir/$item` for each entry (see `dotfiles/bin/wt`, function `_wt_run_setup`)\n- **wt-sync**: existing worktrees can get the symlink via `wt-sync` (already handles the `shared:` list)\n- **No dotfiles or mandible changes needed**\n\n## Related issues\n\n- `0f1af24`: Symlink _artifacts/ children into results/ (navigation convenience, different problem)\n- `58415d2`: Original gitignore role-based split\n- dotfiles `e74e38e`: Add worktree.yaml post-merge dependency sync to global hook (related pattern, different repo)","files":null}]}